    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm studying music theory and im a bit stuck. can u explain why a minor second interval, like C to C#, sounds so dissonant and unstable compared to something like a perfect fifth? i'd like to understand it from an acoustics perspective, maybe something about frequency ratios or how the ear processes it.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "One key reason the minor second interval is perceived as dissonant is due to its frequency ratio. The ratio of adjacent semitones in a minor second is approximately 2:1 (from C to C#), which results in a relatively close proximity of the frequencies, causing potential interference and beats. In contrast, perfect fifths typically have a ratio of 7:8 or 9:10, creating a sense of tension release. Our ears are wired to perceive intervals with more distinct frequency ratios as more stable and consonant.",
